WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:18.640
Alright, here we are at Layer 3 in the OSI model.

00:18.640 --> 00:35.640
We've been slowly moving up.

00:35.640 --> 00:38.720
Alright, here we are at Layer 3 in the OSI model.

00:38.720 --> 00:40.800
We've been slowly moving up.

00:40.800 --> 00:48.040
Now if you remember how we equated the OSI model to a team, like a sports team for example,

00:48.040 --> 00:53.280
usually you pick a captain of the team and that person is usually the one that has the

00:53.280 --> 00:59.680
most leadership qualities, can inspire the others, can coordinate so that the team more

00:59.680 --> 01:01.880
effectively achieves its goal.

01:01.880 --> 01:07.240
Well, if you were to pick a captain of the OSI team, it would have to be the network

01:07.240 --> 01:08.240
layer.

01:08.240 --> 01:13.120
The network layer has some protocols within it that are really fundamental to what

01:13.120 --> 01:18.400
networking is and how we allow communications across network itself.

01:18.400 --> 01:23.680
And so the network layer and protocols that operate here that are part of TCPIP.

01:23.680 --> 01:31.160
Remember how we implement the OSI model is through TCPIP and its family of protocols.

01:31.160 --> 01:35.960
So there are protocols that operate at the network layer here that really drive everything

01:35.960 --> 01:39.120
that happens and are the captain of the team.

01:39.120 --> 01:42.080
That protocol has to be IP.

01:42.080 --> 01:47.800
In fact, if you remember what we talked about earlier as far as the network layer is concerned,

01:47.800 --> 01:55.920
it's really responsible for two really important capabilities and responsibilities that need

01:55.920 --> 01:58.160
to happen across network.

01:58.160 --> 02:00.400
And it's what you see here on your slide.

02:00.400 --> 02:06.960
The first is what we call fragmentation, which means, for example, taking the email that

02:06.960 --> 02:14.480
I'm sending you and breaking it down or fragmenting it into manageable chunks that are typically

02:14.480 --> 02:17.240
called packets or data grams.

02:17.240 --> 02:22.960
But then it's also the network layer through IP here that needs to deliver each of those

02:22.960 --> 02:29.160
data grams to the destination using some sort of addressing scheme, which you know is

02:29.160 --> 02:32.400
referred to as IP addressing.

02:32.400 --> 02:38.760
So remember that the network layer includes the IP protocol, which is really responsible

02:38.760 --> 02:45.520
for two very important things, fragmentation and addressing of those fragments so that

02:45.520 --> 02:47.600
they can get to their destination.

02:47.600 --> 02:55.960
Now, if we draw this, the unit of information that the network layer or IP uses at the network

02:56.040 --> 02:59.400
layer is usually referred to as a packet.

02:59.400 --> 03:03.720
But more appropriately, it should be called a data gram.

03:03.720 --> 03:11.120
So if you look at what a data gram looks like, it really has two important components

03:11.120 --> 03:17.640
to allow the network layer here and IP to not only deliver that information to you, but

03:17.640 --> 03:19.800
as effectively as possible.

03:19.800 --> 03:24.520
So if you look at the two components that make up a data gram or a packet, you're going

03:24.520 --> 03:33.720
to have the data portion, which is also referred to as the payload by some people, most network

03:33.720 --> 03:35.720
people will call it the payload.

03:35.720 --> 03:41.120
But in order to get this data gram to its destination, we need addressing information

03:41.120 --> 03:48.080
that is usually included in what we call the header portion of the data gram.

03:48.080 --> 03:54.640
So this is the unit that IP, for example, uses at the network layer to do fragmentation,

03:54.640 --> 04:00.400
which means breaking that email into data grams, but then allowing each of these data grams

04:00.400 --> 04:02.800
to be delivered to its destination.

04:02.800 --> 04:07.920
So those are the two important functions that the network layer through IP takes care

04:07.920 --> 04:08.920
of.

04:08.920 --> 04:15.680
Now, obviously what's important here is there needs to be fields in the header portion

04:15.680 --> 04:21.000
of the data gram that allows this entire data gram to be delivered to its destination.

04:21.000 --> 04:28.040
So there are fields in here called source IP address, destination IP address, and some

04:28.040 --> 04:35.280
other fields that allow fragmentation and delivery through addressing, for example, at the network

04:35.280 --> 04:36.280
layer.

04:36.280 --> 04:44.960
Now that field called source IP address and destination IP address are 32 bits of information.

04:44.960 --> 04:47.080
32 bits.

04:47.080 --> 04:53.720
And what they've done is they've taken those 32 bits and divided it into four groups

04:53.720 --> 04:55.320
of eight bits.

04:55.320 --> 05:00.320
That's why you end up seeing IP addresses like the one you see on your slide here, right?

05:00.320 --> 05:08.360
So you've got IP addresses that might look like something like this.

05:08.360 --> 05:13.840
But really this represents the 32 bits that are in the header portion of the data gram.

05:13.840 --> 05:19.280
You've just taken those 32 bits and divided it into four groups of eight bits.

05:19.280 --> 05:26.120
Now if you do the math because this is bits, if you've got something that's 32 bits, there

05:26.120 --> 05:32.680
are only so many finite, unique IP addresses that that can represent.

05:32.680 --> 05:42.520
So if you do two to the 32 and work that out, it's going to equal just under 4.3 billion

05:42.520 --> 05:48.800
unique IP addresses that can be referenced across any network like the internet.

05:48.800 --> 05:52.360
And so that's a limitation that we have known about.

05:52.360 --> 05:59.200
And something that has saved us in allowing us to have many more things connected to the

05:59.200 --> 06:04.280
internet rather than this limitation is something called NAT that we're going to talk about

06:04.280 --> 06:05.560
later on.

06:05.560 --> 06:11.960
But this limitation that the industry has known for a number of years has led to the development

06:11.960 --> 06:16.200
of something called IP version 6, which we're going to talk about later on.

06:16.200 --> 06:22.440
But one of the things that they've done in IP version 6 is they've expanded the addressing

06:22.440 --> 06:29.480
to actually 128 bits for both the source IP address and the destination IP address.

06:29.480 --> 06:34.880
And something else that's relevant from a security perspective in IP version 6 is the

06:34.880 --> 06:44.400
inclusion of security called IPSec, which will add authentication and encryption natively

06:44.400 --> 06:50.160
into the IP version 6 protocol when everybody's using it.

06:50.160 --> 06:55.760
And so the next thing that you see up here on your slide is not anything that's relevant

06:55.760 --> 07:02.600
from the perspective of you having to understand each of these different IEEE document numbers

07:02.600 --> 07:04.040
that you see here.

07:04.040 --> 07:09.280
The important thing to remember at this point is the importance of that organization called

07:09.280 --> 07:10.840
the IEEE.

07:10.840 --> 07:16.080
The IEEE is the Institute of Electric and Electronic Engineers.

07:16.080 --> 07:21.520
And they are a bunch of bright people that get together when a technology first appears

07:21.520 --> 07:23.760
or improves, for example.

07:23.760 --> 07:29.760
And what they do is they sit down and ratify, which means they agree on what a technology

07:29.760 --> 07:35.680
needs to look like so that vendors and anyone else that wants to offer products related

07:35.680 --> 07:42.160
to that technology will have to conform to the standards and not go off in their own direction.

07:42.160 --> 07:47.840
And so when they ratify some of these technologies and what they need to look like, they issue

07:47.840 --> 07:51.000
what are called IEEE document numbers.

07:51.000 --> 07:59.720
And you're probably familiar with the family of 802.11 IEEE specifications for wireless

07:59.720 --> 08:00.720
lands.

08:00.720 --> 08:07.760
And as we've evolved, for example, what we used to have was 802.11A and then B came

08:07.760 --> 08:13.560
along and then G came along and then N came along and AC came along, they've ratified

08:13.560 --> 08:18.040
each of those standards so that everybody conforms to those standards.

08:18.040 --> 08:20.760
That's the importance of the IEEE.

08:20.760 --> 08:25.040
So there's different specifications for different technologies that exist out there.

08:25.040 --> 08:28.800
You don't need to memorize them all, obviously, for purposes of the exam.

